author: Oliver Adey
title: Celtics' Nicolas K√ºhn: The Evolution from "Super Kid" to Impact Player in the Old Firm Rivalry
text:
Nicolas K√ºhn, a once-promising young talent in German football, has found his stride at Celtic FC. Despite a rocky path marked by challenges and setbacks, including a recent Old Firm derby defeat, he reflects on his journey with optimism. Now a key player, he has scored 18 goals this season, helping the team aim for their 55th championship title. His resilience and dedication showcase a passion for the game, highlighting his evolution from a child prodigy to a star in Glasgow.
Nicolas K√ºhn: From a Young Prodigy to Celtic Star Nicolas K√ºhn has long been recognized as a promising talent in Germany since his childhood. However, his journey has not always unfolded as expected. Now thriving at Celtic, K√ºhn shares his experiences, aspirations, and dreams in a recent interview.
On New Year‚Äôs Day, K√ºhn celebrated his birthday surrounded by family. However, he prefers not to dwell on the following day. It wasn‚Äôt about the presents or drinks, as he abstains from alcohol. Instead, January 2nd marked a disappointing moment for K√ºhn and his team, Celtic Glasgow, as they faced a 0-3 defeat to their fierce rivals, the Rangers.
In the aftermath of the match, television cameras captured the jubilant celebration of thousands of Rangers supporters clad in their blue gear. In stark contrast, K√ºhn donned a green-and-white Celtic jersey with the number ten, standing silently among his fellow fans who also refrained from cheering.
The Intensity of the Old Firm Rivalry As the rematch against the Rangers approaches on March 16th, 2025, K√ºhn, now 25, reflects on his initial loss in the historic Old Firm derby, a rivalry steeped in more than just football. He acknowledges the significance of this match, which embodies deep-rooted religious and political tensions between the two clubs. ‚ÄúEvery derby is incredible,‚Äù he remarks, eagerly anticipating the next encounter.
K√ºhn joined Celtic in January 2024 from Rapid Vienna, and the meaning of an Old Firm match was clear to him from the start. Prior to the recent loss, he had faced the Rangers five times without defeat, contributing to his team‚Äôs collection of three titles during his time there. With a 16-point lead over the Rangers and only three games left in the regular season, Celtic is poised to claim yet another championship.
Celtic fans are dreaming of the coveted 55th championship title, and K√ºhn is playing a pivotal role in that ambition. This season, he has netted 18 goals and provided 13 assists across 41 competitive matches. The fans have even crafted a song in his honor, celebrating his dynamic play and goal-scoring ability.
With a playing style reminiscent of football great Arjen Robben, K√ºhn‚Äôs movements on the pitch have become a nightmare for opposing defenders. His agility and precision are key elements that have contributed to his growing reputation.
Once heralded as a child prodigy, K√ºhn‚Äôs path to success wasn‚Äôt straightforward. Starting at a young age, he transitioned from a local club in Lower Saxony to FC St. Pauli, then Hannover 96, and eventually RB Leipzig, where he caught the eye of renowned coach Ralf Rangnick. Despite early accolades, including the prestigious ‚ÄòFritz-Walter-Medaille,‚Äô his journey included challenges at Leipzig and Ajax, where he struggled for playing time.
After a challenging period that included personal loss and injuries, K√ºhn found his footing during a loan spell at Erzgebirge Aue, where he made a significant impact in the 2. Bundesliga. His successful stint there paved the way for his move to Rapid Vienna, and ultimately, to the illustrious Celtic FC.
Now, nestled in the heart of Glasgow, K√ºhn has embraced his role as a key player, often opting for a hat while shopping to maintain a low profile as he navigates the adoring fanbase. Yet, on the pitch, he leaves no room for modesty, especially during his performances in the Champions League, where he showcased his talent against former club Leipzig, scoring two goals.
‚ÄúThose were beautiful moments,‚Äù K√ºhn reflects. His story is one of resilience and passion for the beautiful game, proving that with perseverance, dreams can indeed be realized.

text: La resoluci√≥n, aprobada por la m√≠nima diferencia, tuvo como coauspiciadoras a las concejales boricuas Rossana Rodr√≠guez S√°nchez y Jessie Fuentes 1 de febrero de 2024 - 9:49 PM La resoluci√≥n, aprobada por la m√≠nima diferencia, tuvo como coauspiciadoras a las concejales boricuas Rossana Rodr√≠guez S√°nchez y Jessie Fuentes 1 de febrero de 2024 - 9:49 PM Washington D. C. ‚Äì Con el voto decisivo del alcalde Brandon Johnson, el Concejo Municipal de Chicago aprob√≥ el mi√©rcoles (24-23) una resoluci√≥n que aboga porque cese el fuego en la guerra entre Israel y Hamas, que tiene lugar en la franja de Gaza, y se liberen a todos los rehenes. La resoluci√≥n tuvo entre las promotoras originales a las concejales municipales puertorrique√±as Rossana Rodr√≠guez S√°nchez (distrito 33) y Jessie Fuentes, quien representa el antiguo barrio boricua de la ciudad, la tercera de m√°s poblaci√≥n en Estados Unidos. Para romper el debate, tras un contencioso debate, se requiri√≥ el voto del alcalde Johnson. ‚ÄúCreo que es necesario tener estas conversaciones. De eso se trata la democracia. ¬øQu√© estamos haciendo si en realidad no decimos las cosas que hay que decir, especialmente ante un genocidio? Lo que estamos haciendo hoy es un ejercicio importante‚Äù, indic√≥ la concejal Rodr√≠guez S√°nchez, seg√∫n la publicaci√≥n Politico. La concejal Debra Silverstein, la √∫nica jud√≠a en la legislatura municipal, critic√≥ la medida, por entender que no deben haber concesiones mientras Hamas no se comprometa a cesar sus ataques y debido a que contradice la pol√≠tica exterior del presidente Joe Biden, ‚Äúa quien hemos invitado‚Äù este agosto a Chicago, como parte de la convenci√≥n presidencial dem√≥cratas. ‚Äú¬øC√≥mo se apoya una resoluci√≥n que permite que un r√©gimen terrorista permanezca en el poder para que pueda seguir atacando al √∫nico Estado jud√≠o del mundo, un Estado democr√°tico con un 20% de poblaci√≥n musulmana y cristiana?‚Äù. cuestion√≥ Silverstein, electa por el distrito 50. Por su parte, el concejal municipal Daniel LaSpata, electo por el primer distrito de la ciudad, sostuvo que el mi√©rcoles votaron ‚Äúcon esperanza, con solidaridad...para ayudar a la gente a sentirse escuchada en un mundo de silencio‚Äù. Seg√∫n Reuters, cerca de 70 concejos municipales en Estados Unidos, incluidos los de ciudades como Detroit (Michigan), San Francisco (California) y Atlanta (Georgia) tambi√©n han aprobado resoluciones en favor de un cese el fuego, en respuesta a un conflicto en el que han muerto sobre 26,000 palestinos, principalmente ni√±os y mujeres, y que se desat√≥ tras el ataque del 7 de octubre de Hamas en Israel que cost√≥ m√°s de 1,200 vidas y en el que tomaron como rehenes a unas 250 personas. title: El Liverpool sigue a lo suyo y ya le saca 14 puntos al City
text:
El Liverpool sigue a lo suyo y ya le saca 14 puntos al City
Los reds, que tuvieron que remontar, se llevaron los tres puntos gracias a loa goles de Gakpo, Jones y Salah.
En medio de una niebla tremenda en Liverpool y con el escenario del 'Boxing Day' de fondo, el l√≠der de la Premier League ampli√≥ su ventaja al remontar al Leicester City (3-1) y, pese a tener un partido menos, tiene una ventaja de siete puntos sobre el Chelsea y de catorce sobre el Manchester City.
Los de Arne Slot cerraron la jornada del 'Boxing Day' con un trabajado triunfo ante el Leicester City, que solo necesit√≥ seis minutos para adelantarse por medio de Jordan Ayew, pero que acab√≥ notando la presi√≥n y arrollo del mejor equipo de Europa.
Le cost√≥, eso s√≠, a los 'Reds' sacudirse el susto inicial, cuando Ayew bail√≥ en el √°rea a Andy Robertson y sac√≥ un disparo a la media vuelta que toc√≥ en Van Dijk lo justo para desviar la trayectoria a Alisson. Fue un tanto sorprendente en un Anfield que tras una racha de nueve victorias seguidas en casa pinch√≥ la jornada pasada contra el Fulham y se temi√≥ un resultado parecido ante el conjunto de Ruud Van Nistelrooy.

Los 'Foxes', candidatos claros a descender, se aliaron con la fortuna y sortearon tres veces el empate gracias a la madera.Mohamed Salah, en dos ocasiones, y Andy Robertson, en un cabezazo, se estrellaron en el palo, hasta que antes del descanso, en el tiempo de descuento, Cody Gakpo dibuj√≥ una par√°bola a la escuadra para cimentar la remontada del Liverpool.
El golazo del holand√©s, que ya lleva once dianas esta temporada, alivi√≥ a los de Slot, que se fueron al descanso sabiendo que la segunda parte dictaminar√≠a sentencia para un Leicester que se hab√≠a conformado desde el 0-1 y que pensaba que ese gol de Ayew le podr√≠a valer para llegar hasta el final con vida.
Pero no tard√≥ ni cinco minutos el Liverpool en poner el 2-1. Curtis Jones en el primer palo culmin√≥ una gran combinaci√≥n iniciada por Salah y continuada con un pase raso de Alexis Mac Allister. Jones empuj√≥ la pelota de primeras y, pese a que el VAR revis√≥ un posible fuera de juego, el tanto subi√≥ al marcador y el Liverpool respir√≥ tranquilo.
El fara√≥n quiere la Premier üåü

Las ocasiones empezaron a fluir y, aunque a Gakpo le anularon su doblete por un fuera de juego de Darwin N√∫√±ez, lo que no se pudo evitar fue el tanto de Salah, el decimosexto de esta Premier League.
El egipcio encar√≥ a su par y su nivel de confianza es tal que no le import√≥ tener a dos jugadores por delante. Clav√≥ la pelota en el palo largo y se dirigi√≥ a la grada con los brazos abiertos. Esta le respondi√≥ con su c√°ntico habitual y solo queda que la directiva de Anfield le ofrezca un nuevo contrato.
Es el mejor jugador de la liga y, pese a llevar un partido menos que el resto, ha generado 16 goles y once asistencias. Es, con diferencia, el mejor goleador y el mejor asistente de la competici√≥n.
A nivel grupal, el Liverpool, con un partido menos, tiene 42 puntos, siete m√°s que el Chelsea y ocho m√°s que el Nottingham Forest. Si ganara el Arsenal al Ipswich Town este viernes, el equipo de Mikel Arteta se colocar√≠a como el m√°ximo perseguidor, con una desventaja de seis unidades.

title: Our Blood Institute in need of donors during emergency blood shortage
text:
Our Blood Institute in need of donors during emergency blood shortage
ARDMORE, Okla. (KXII) - As Texoma temperatures dropped, things seemed to screech to a halt, but the need for donating blood never freezes. Right now, Our Blood Institute, formerly Oklahoma Blood Institute, which services southern Oklahoma, is suffering an emergency blood shortage.
‚ÄúThere is a sense of urgency, that‚Äôs why we‚Äôre in a blood emergency,‚Äù said Michelle McGuire, OBI Senior Account Manager. ‚ÄúA blood emergency means that we have a day supply of blood or less for the whole state, and that‚Äôs a very scary situation to be in... If we don‚Äôt see something turn around and we improve those collections, then that‚Äôs a recipe for disaster that we‚Äôre trying to avoid.‚Äù
OBI has a daily unit mark they have to meet to help countless people get the blood they need just to survive, but currently, that is in jeopardy.
‚ÄúCancer patients, accident victims, people that are having surgery, newborn babies on NICU up at children‚Äôs hospital, and then if something major happened, we wouldn‚Äôt be able to provide that supply that‚Äôs needed,‚Äù McGuire said.
With the importance of donating blood as critical as it is, people around the city of Ardmore are stepping up to help.
‚ÄúI know how important it is for each of us to donate and to do our civic duty is what I believe it is,‚Äù said Ardmore Assistant City Manager Kevin Norris.
‚ÄúAt the end of the day, you‚Äôre saving three people when you donate blood, and it might be your next-door neighbor,‚Äù said McGuire. ‚ÄúIt might be someone you pass on the road. You just never know who‚Äôs going to need those units.‚Äù
If you donate now, you‚Äôll get a themed donor t-shirt too; a gift for being a superhero to those who need it.

author: Advertising Standards Authority | Committee of Advertising Practice
title: Annual Report 2023: Building our world-leading AI capability - ASA | CAP
text:
Our new Annual Report 2023 highlights how our world-leading AI-based Active Ad Monitoring system is delivering significant positive impact in our regulation of UK ads.
Annual Report 2023 - Introduction from Guy Parker, CEO In 2023, our Active Ad Monitoring system, which captures large volumes of online ads from channels including social media, search and display and uses in-house machine learning models to assess them, processed a total of 3 million ads over the course of the year. That figure is projected to be over 10 million in 2024. It has expanded our visibility of online advertising, allowing our experts to make more informed decisions and spot and tackle irresponsible ads more quickly, and is increasingly providing us with intelligence on where compliance with the Advertising Code is high.
Read our new Annual Report in full.
In line with our new strategy, ‚ÄòAI-assisted, collective ad regulation‚Äô, launched last year, the report highlights how we have prioritised proactive regulatory projects, further shifting away from complaints-led investigations towards front-foot ASA-led monitoring and enforcement action. This helped support the ASA‚Äôs focus on tackling ad-related societal concerns in areas such as green claims, youth vaping, body image, gambling and prescription-only-medicines.
Adopting a ‚Äòwhole system‚Äô approach to issues that cause the most detriment to people, we‚Äôve:
Continued to deliver key strands of our Climate Change and Environment project including cracking down on misleading claims in the energy and transport sectors such as sustainability claims for airlines and misleading omissions by oil and gas companies
Worked in partnership with the Competition and Markets Authority on shared priorities such as claims for greener homes and the Financial Conduct Authority on green finance
Published research and new guidance on recycling, biodegradable and compostable claims and engaged with and offered support through CAP‚Äôs Copy Advice service to businesses who want to make environmental claims
Further examined the potential harm arising from the use of digitally altered images in ads, holding two roundtable events, one with parliamentarians, academics, third sector, advertisers and publishers and another, facilitated by a children‚Äôs charity, to hear young people‚Äôs own experiences and observations on the impact of digitally enhanced images in ads on body image
Launched multiple investigations and begun enforcement action against ads that trivialised the decision to have cosmetic surgery overseas, pressured consumers and omitted material information about pre-consultations and where they would take place
Taken a cross-organisational approach ‚Äì through investigations, monitoring, enforcement and guidance ‚Äì to address concerns about vaping ads appearing in social media and being targeted at or likely to appeal to under-18s
All these strands of work were enhanced through expanding the capacity of our Active Ad Monitoring system.
Other key statistics from the ASA and CAP reveal that in 2023:
The ASA received 39,034 complaints (up 16%) about 25,041 ads (up 19%)
27,378 ads were amended or withdrawn as a result of ASA work
92% of ads amended or withdrawn resulted from our proactive work, including use of our Active Ad Monitoring system, and 89% of those were non-paid ads online
CAP delivered 1,369,887 pieces of advice and training to businesses
Online continues to be the most complained about media ‚Äì 20,944 complaints (up 14%) about 17,174 ads (up 17%)
TV remains the second most complained about media ‚Äì 13,604 complaints (up 19%) about 4,399 ads (up 12%)
Email overtook outdoor to become the third most complained about media ‚Äì 1,210 complaints about 1,058 ads
The report also sets out how we brought greater transparency and broader accountability to our work online through a world-first pilot with platforms and intermediaries. Our Intermediary and Platform Principles (IPP) pilot tried and tested ways in which platforms and intermediaries can play a part, and be seen to play a part, in supporting the ASA to help secure responsible advertising online. We welcome the Government‚Äôs view that IPP is a significant positive development for the advertising industry. We will now advocate for a second version of IPP that is permanent, comprehensive and effective.
ASA Chief Executive, Guy Parker says: ‚ÄúOur investment in data science and AI is equipping us with the tools to deliver more effective ad regulation. It supports the work of our expert teams and is increasingly core to our monitoring and enforcement activities through the intelligence it gives us and that we can act on. It helps us to remain flexible and adapt quickly to safeguard the interests of consumers and citizens, especially the young and vulnerable, in the rapidly changing digital landscape. And we continue to focus on our proactive work, across media as well as online, to prevent irresponsible ads appearing in the first place.‚Äù
Read our full Annual Report 2023 now.
